  <h2>I've Shipped Enough Printers to Know What Goes Wrong</h2>

  <p>
    Between building out the 3D3D network, deploying printers for events, and buying used machines, I've shipped and received more 3D printers than I can count. I've also unpacked a few that arrived in pieces. Cracked frames, snapped bowden tubes, bent gantry rods, shattered glass beds. Every single one of those failures was preventable.
  </p>

  <p>
    Whether you're relocating your workshop, selling a printer online, or deploying one to a remote site, here's what actually works.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 1: Remove Everything That Moves</h2>

  <p>
    This is where most people skip ahead and regret it. Before you even think about boxes and foam, strip the printer down:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Remove the build plate.</strong> Glass beds crack. PEI spring steel bends. Wrap it separately in bubble wrap and cardboard.</li>
    <li><strong>Remove the spool holder and any filament.</strong> Spool holders are lever arms waiting to snap off.</li>
    <li><strong>Disconnect the bowden tube</strong> if your printer has one. It'll get snagged and either pop the fitting or crack the hotend mount.</li>
    <li><strong>Remove the nozzle</strong> or at minimum put a silicone sock on it. A bare nozzle poking around inside a box does damage.</li>
    <li><strong>Zip-tie the print head to the gantry.</strong> Use two zip ties, one for X travel, one for Y. You want zero movement.</li>
    <li><strong>Lock the Z axis.</strong> On bed-slingers, zip-tie the bed to the lowest position. On CoreXY, secure the gantry so it can't drop.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 2: The Original Box Is Your Best Friend</h2>

  <p>
    If you still have the original packaging, the molded foam inserts, the factory box, use it. Printer manufacturers spend real engineering time designing those inserts. They're shaped to support the frame at load-bearing points and prevent movement in all three axes.
  </p>

  <p>
    I keep every printer box I receive. They stack flat against a wall when empty and they're worth their weight when you need to move a machine. If you threw yours out, read on.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 3: No Original Box? Build a Crate</h2>

  <p>
    For printers without original packaging, I build a simple crate from half-inch plywood or OSB. It doesn't need to be furniture-grade. It needs to be rigid.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Cut a base slightly larger than the printer footprint, at least 5cm clearance on all sides</li>
    <li>Screw the printer down to the base using the rubber feet mounting points (most printers have M4 or M5 holes in the feet)</li>
    <li>Build four walls and a top, screw construction, not nails. You want to be able to disassemble it on the other end</li>
    <li>Fill the void space with expanding foam, crumpled packing paper, or rigid foam blocks. The printer should not shift at all inside the crate</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This sounds like overkill until you watch a courier huck your box off a truck. Then it sounds about right.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 4: Choosing a Carrier</h2>

  <p>
    Standard parcel post (Canada Post, UPS, FedEx) is fine for small printers under 15kg total packed weight, things like an Ender 3 or Bambu A1 mini. Slap a "FRAGILE" sticker on it, add insurance, and ship with tracking.
  </p>

  <p>
    For larger machines — anything with a full enclosure, use freight shipping. LTL (less than truckload) carriers handle palletized goods and the handling is generally better than parcel post. Strap the crate to a pallet, shrink-wrap it, and book it as a skid.
  </p>

  <p>
    For local moves under 200km, just drive it yourself. Put the printer on the floor of your vehicle (not the seat), wedge it with blankets, and avoid potholes. I've moved printers in the back of a pickup truck with a tarp and ratchet straps and they arrived fine.
  </p>

  <h2>Step 5: Receiving and Setup</h2>

  <p>
    When the printer arrives, don't just plug it in and start printing. Check everything:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Inspect the frame for cracks or bends, run a straightedge along the extrusions</li>
    <li>Check belt tension, belts loosen during shipping from vibration</li>
    <li>Level the bed and run a first-layer calibration</li>
    <li>Check all cable connections, vibration can work JST connectors loose</li>
    <li>Run a test print before committing to a real job</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Field Deployment Is a Different Game</h2>

  <p>
    Shipping a printer to a boat or a remote job site adds another layer. For the Newport Bermuda campaign, we're thinking about how to secure a printer in a marine environment where the floor moves. Custom mounts, vibration damping, quick-disconnect power. That's a whole other post.
  </p>

  <p>
    But the basics stay the same: immobilize everything that moves, protect everything that breaks, and never trust a courier to care about your stuff as much as you do.
  </p>
